Spotify Dataset Exploration¶

Data Gathering¶

Spotify allows its users to be able to download his/her music play history and the app usage history over the past year (1 year only), in this case July 2019 - July 2020.¶

This data is used to perform the aforementioned analysis. This data can be downloaded by placing a request to Spotify, they will send a link to download the data in the form of zip files.¶

# A function to retrieve the URI of each song in the dataframe based on the artist name and track name.

def get_song_URI(artist, title):
    query = title + ' ' + artist
    res = sp.search(query)
    for i in res['tracks']['items']:
        if (i['artists'][0]['name'] == artist) and (i['name'] == title):
            return i['uri']
        else:
            try:
                return res['tracks']['items'][0]['uri']
            except:
                # No results for artist and title
                return "Cannot Find URI"

Here, we use pandas apply() function to add values row by row to our URI column. So, we use the artist name and track name, send it to the above function and store the appropriate value for the URI.

Some songs do not have a URI, this could be due to 2 reasons

  1. It is not a song, probably a podcast.
  2. It has been deleted or taken down by Spotify and does not exist anymore.

Hence, they must be removed because we can only get features of the song (danceability, energy etc.. ) if the song has a valid URI associated to it.

This removal is done in 2 steps:

  1. Fetch all the rows which don't have a URI, this will include podcasts also.
  2. Append them to the dataframe twice and remove the duplicates and save the resultant dataframe into a csv file.

Next step is to fetch the song features using the songs which have a URI associated to them. We use the _audiofeatures() function of the spotify python API, to fetch the features by supplying the song URI.¶

In [ ]:
for uri in list(songs_df.URI):
    row = songs_df.query('URI == @uri')
    features = sp.audio_features(uri)[0]
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'danceability'] = features['danceability']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'energy'] = features['energy']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'key'] = features['key']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'loudness'] = features['loudness']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'mode'] = features['mode']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'speechiness'] = features['speechiness']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'acousticness'] = features['acousticness']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'instrumentalness'] = features['instrumentalness']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'liveness'] = features['liveness']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'valence'] = features['valence']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'tempo'] = features['tempo']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'duration_ms'] = features['duration_ms']
    songs_df.loc[row.index, 'time_signature'] = features['time_signature']

I have also tried to fetch the lyrics of some of the songs using the Genius API. It must be noted that, not all of the songs I listen to are of the english language. I have heard songs from Hindi, Telugu, Kannada, French, Spanish, Urdu and others. So, some of the song lyrics are not available on Genius.¶

Out of the various music lyrics retrieval APIs available, only genius provided the full lyrics of songs, without charge, hence it was chosen.¶

In [3]:
GENIUS_CLIENT_ACCESS_TOKEN = os.environ.get('GENIUS_CLIENT_ACCESS_TOKEN')
api = genius.Genius(GENIUS_CLIENT_ACCESS_TOKEN, sleep_time=0.01, verbose=False)
In [4]:
cols = ['album','featuredArtists', 'lyrics', 'year']
for col in cols:
    songs_df[col] = np.nan

songs_df['featuredArtists'] = songs_df['featuredArtists'].astype('object')

The way the lyrics are retrieved is as follows:

  1. I search for songs which have the given artist name and track name.
  2. I choose the first result from the returned list of songs on Genius.

The lyrics and the audio features are moved to a new file, each row is appended to a file in the same directory.

In [5]:
headers = list(songs_df)
total = songs_df.shape[0]
start_time = datetime.now()
print("Started at {}".format(start_time))
with open('complete_songs_data.csv', 'a+', newline='') as file:
    dictWriter = DictWriter(file, fieldnames=headers)
    for i in songs_df.index.to_list():
        rolling_pct = int((i / total) * 100)
        print(str(rolling_pct) + "%" + " Collecting " + str(i) +" of " + str(total) + " "*50, end="\r")
        trackName = songs_df['trackName'].iloc[i]
        trackName = re.sub(" and ", " & ", trackName)
        artistName = songs_df['artistName'].iloc[i]
        artistName = re.sub(" and ", " & ", artistName)
        try:
            song = api.search_song(trackName, artist=artistName)
            album = song.album
            featuredArtists = song.featured_artists
            lyrics = re.sub("\n", " ", song.lyrics)
            year = song.year
        except:
            album = np.nan
            featuredArtists = np.nan
            lyrics = np.nan
            year = np.nan
        row = {
                'endTime': songs_df.endTime.iloc[i],
                'artistName': songs_df.artistName.iloc[i],
                'trackName': songs_df.trackName.iloc[i],
                'msPlayed': songs_df.msPlayed.iloc[i],
                'duration_ms': songs_df.duration_ms.iloc[i],
                'URI': songs_df.URI.iloc[i],
                'danceability': songs_df.danceability.iloc[i],
                'energy': songs_df.energy.iloc[i],
                'key': songs_df.key.iloc[i],
                'loudness': songs_df.loudness.iloc[i],
                'mode': songs_df["mode"].iloc[i],
                'speechiness': songs_df.speechiness.iloc[i],
                'acousticness': songs_df.acousticness.iloc[i],
                'instrumentalness': songs_df.instrumentalness.iloc[i],
                'liveness': songs_df.liveness.iloc[i],
                'valence': songs_df.valence.iloc[i],
                'tempo': songs_df.tempo.iloc[i],
                'time_signature': songs_df.time_signature.iloc[i],
                'album': album,
                'featuredArtists': featuredArtists,
                'lyrics': lyrics,
                'year': year
            }
        dictWriter.writerow(row)
end_time = datetime.now()

print("Total time to collect: {}".format(end_time - start_time))

Here I wanted to check how many songs I was listening to, on an average, through out the course of a day.

3. Now I wanted to check the relation between the streaming patterns over days of week and hours of day.¶

This required a groupby operation on the dataframe.

In [7]:
day_hr_count = spotify_data_songs.groupby(
    [spotify_data_songs.endTime.dt.dayofweek, spotify_data_songs.endTime.dt.hour]
).count()['trackName']
day_hr_count.index.set_names(["day", "hour"], inplace=True)

    sub = sub + 1

From the above graphs the following observations can be made:¶

  1. Saturdays I sleep late, as the number of songs played during the hours 0 - 5 is higher than on other days.
  2. Mondays and Sundays, I listen to a lot of songs in the early hours 5 - 10, due to the rising nature of the graph in those hours, as opposed to other days.
  3. Thursdays followed by Tuesdays appear to be the most productive days because lesser number of songs are played during the morning hours 5 - 15.
  4. Friday midnight ( Thursday late nights ), I listen to very few songs, because of the vertically downward nature of the graph.
  5. Wednesday is the one weekday, where I listen to a lot of songs. In fact, the peaks are higher than the weekend. So, Wednesday is the least productive weekday.

In [297]:
def get_wordcloud(month_df):
    month_df = pd.DataFrame(month_df.lyrics.dropna())
    month_df.lyrics = month_df.lyrics.str.replace(r'\[.*\]|\(.*\)', '')
    all_words = ""
    for song in month_df.lyrics:
        tokens = song.split() 
        for i in range(len(tokens)): 
            tokens[i] = tokens[i].lower()
        for words in tokens:
            all_words += words + ' '
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width = 800, height = 800, 
                background_color ='white', 
                stopwords = stopwords,
                min_font_size = 10).generate(all_words) 
    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 8), facecolor = None) 
    plt.imshow(wordcloud) 
    plt.axis("off") 
    plt.tight_layout(pad = 0) 
    plt.show()
